1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,520
Now let's talk about generators.

2

00:00:02,520  -->  00:00:06,460
If you remember our cookie baking example from earlier,

3

00:00:06,460  -->  00:00:08,300
in our busy bakery,

4

00:00:08,300  -->  00:00:10,620
we will receive multiple orders for cookies,

5

00:00:10,620  -->  00:00:13,680
but we don't want to bake thousands of cookies all at once.

6

00:00:13,680  -->  00:00:15,110
That would not be efficient,

7

00:00:15,110  -->  00:00:20,300
and lots of cookies would be left out waiting around and not ready to be eaten by anyone.

8

00:00:20,300  -->  00:00:26,140
Generators are ideal for this type of task as they let you yield one batch at a time,

9

00:00:26,140  -->  00:00:28,640
pausing and resuming as needed.

10

00:00:28,640  -->  00:00:31,520
This helps you save memory and

11

00:00:31,520  -->  00:00:35,495
ensures that you're only producing cookies as you need them.

12

00:00:35,495  -->  00:00:41,010
Let's see how to use generators to yield a limited number of batches,

13

00:00:41,010  -->  00:00:45,570
such as if you know the exact number of orders to make in a given day,

14

00:00:45,570  -->  00:00:49,950
and how to yield batches indefinitely if you want to just make

15

00:00:49,950  -->  00:00:52,130
cookies in a batch each time you need

16

00:00:52,130  -->  00:00:55,470
to while tracking how many cookies you've generated.

17

00:00:55,470  -->  00:00:59,070
Let's define a generator function for baking cookies.

18

00:00:59,070  -->  00:01:01,280
We'll use yield instead of return,

19

00:01:01,280  -->  00:01:03,660
allowing the function to pause and

20

00:01:03,660  -->  00:01:06,980
continue baking whenever we're ready for the next batch.

21

00:01:06,980  -->  00:01:10,660
Our bake cookies function will take in a batch size and

22

00:01:10,660  -->  00:01:14,820
also have an optional limit of max batches to make,

23

00:01:14,820  -->  00:01:18,460
but the default if it's not defined is none.

24

00:01:18,460  -->  00:01:24,440
Then we'll set the batch count and total cookies each to zero as we start the generator.

25

00:01:24,440  -->  00:01:30,840
If the max batches is provided as a parameter input when it's not set as none,

26

00:01:30,840  -->  00:01:33,620
the generator will stop when it reaches the limit,

27

00:01:33,620  -->  00:01:36,745
which we define with our while loop logic.

28

00:01:36,745  -->  00:01:42,230
We'll then increment by counting upwards where the batch count increments by one.

29

00:01:42,230  -->  00:01:44,390
This allows the function to pause and

30

00:01:44,390  -->  00:01:47,625
continue baking whenever you're ready for the next batch.

31

